Project CAPSTONE PROJECT- BANK TERM DEPOSIT OFFER CAMPAIGN¶

Problem Statement:¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns (phone calls) of a Portuguese banking institution. The classification goal is to predict if the client will subscribe (yes/no) a term deposit (Response variable).

This dataset is sourced from the IBM Watson Platform- UCI Machine Learning Repository. This data set contains 10% of the examples and 17 inputs, randomly selected from the full data set, bank-full.csv. The full data set is available on the Watson Studio Community as well as at https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Bank+Marketing.

In this project, we will design and deploy a supervised Model(such as Logistics regression) to predict if a Customer will subscribe to a term deposit campaign or not¶

Solution Approach:¶

We will be using Supervised Learning Binary Classification Model, i.e. Logistic regression to predict if the Customer will accept the term deposit offer or not.

Logistic Regression is one of the most valuable machine learning model and is mainly used when the dependent variable is categorical. In our case, term_deposit value is a categorical variable(Yes/No)

def hist_num_td(num_list, num_title, td_flag):
    '''
    Purpose:  Plots the Histograms of Numerical Variables in relation to term_deposit indicator -yes/no    
    
    INPUT
    List 1 - Containing the numerical predictor variables 
    List 2 - Containing the Plot axis title for numerical predictor variables 
    td_flag - term_deposit_flag- Yes or No
   
    OUTPUT
    Historgrams of Numerical variables distribution with respect to term_deposit Indicator(yes/no)
   
    '''

    flag = td_flag
    ROWS, COLS = 2,3
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ROWS,COLS, figsize=(20,15))

    if flag == "no":
        plot_title = "term_deposit = No"
        my_color= "blue"
    else:
        plot_title = "term_deposit= yes"
        my_color= "red"
        
        
    num = 0
    row, col = 0, 0
    for i, num_feat in enumerate(num_list):
        if col == COLS - 1:
            row += 1
        col = i % COLS
      
        clean_bank_df[clean_bank_df.term_deposit == flag][num_feat].hist(bins= 5, color=my_color, alpha=1.0, ax=ax[row,col]).set_title(plot_title)
        ax[row,col].set_xlabel(num_title[i],fontsize = 15,weight='bold')
        ax[row,col].set_ylabel("Accounts Count",fontsize = 15, weight='bold')
        num += 1

    return
    
# Plot the Histogram for Numeric Variable with respect to term deposit Flag = "No"
num_list = ['age', 'balance', 'campaign', 'duration','previous', 'pdays']
num_title= ['age', 'balance', 'campaign', 'duration','previous # of Contacts', 'past days']


td_flag = "no"
hist_num_td(num_list, num_title, td_flag)

# Plot the Histogram for Numeric Variable with respect to term deposit  Flag = "Yes"
td_flag = "yes"    
hist_num_td(num_list, num_title, td_flag)

Note on Imbalanced Data Set¶

Observation on Target Variable distribution As we can see the Imblance situation as the # of Not-Subscribed count is higher than Subscriberd count. This could lead to overfitting and high accuracy as most of the prediction could fall under "Non-Subscribed"

We do need to mitigate the issue of imbalanced dataset:

  • resample data (imbalanced-learn),
  • collect more samples,
  • use precision and recall as accuracy metrics.
  • Use Sagemaker Linear Learner Models with hyperparameter settings -positive_example_weight_mult

Identify and remove outliers using z-Score¶

In [27]:
# Use Z-Score to identify and correct outliers in Bank Data Frame
# Z-score is finding the distribution of data where mean is 0 and standard deviation is 1 i.e. normal distribution.
# while calculating the Z-score we re-scale and center the data and look for data points which are too far from zero.
# These data points which are way too far from zero will be treated as the outliers. 
# In most of the cases a threshold of 3 or -3 is used i.e if the Z-score value is greater than or less than 3 or -3 respectively, that data point will be identified as outliers.

from scipy import stats
import numpy as np
z = np.abs(stats.zscore(final_bank_df))


# define a thrshold to identify outlier
threshold = 3
# print(np.where(z > 3))

# remove outliers 
final_bank_df = final_bank_df[(z < 3).all(axis=1)]

print(final_bank_df.shape)

# dump the final dataframe to excel for review 
final_bank_df.to_excel("bank_output2.xlsx",sheet_name='final')

Validate and Evaluate the Model¶

Grid Search - Hyperparameters Optimization for improving performance¶

This is used to choose the best hyperparameters for the model. The grid search package, GridSearchCV, uses cross validation to evaluate each model with different combinations of hyperparameters. This means that the data set is split into the number of folds specified (in this case, 10) and each unique model is tested with each fold of the data set and evaluated based on the specified metric (here, mean squared error).

In [31]:
# Use grid search to find the optimal combinations of supplied hyperparameters.

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import balanced_accuracy_score

# Create Parameters for GridSearch

 #Cs = np.logspace(-6, -1, 10)

logistic = LogisticRegression()

# Set hyperparamter options
penalty = ['l1', 'l2']
class_weight= ['balanced']
solver = ['liblinear', 'saga']
# Create regularization hyperparameter space
C = np.logspace(0, 4, 10)

# Create hyperparameter options
param_grid= dict(C=C, penalty=penalty,class_weight=class_weight,solver=solver)


#param_grid = {'penalty': ['l1','l2'],'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000], 'class_weight': ['balanced']}

grid_mod = GridSearchCV(logistic,param_grid=param_grid,cv=10,n_jobs=-1, verbose =1,scoring='roc_auc')

# Train the Best Model
final_model = grid_mod.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# View best hyperparameters/score
print("best_score(Mean cross_validated score) :", final_model.best_score_)
print('Best Penalty:', final_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['penalty'])
print('Best C:', final_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['C'])
print('Best Parameters:', final_model.best_estimator_.get_params())

In [34]:
# Let's draw ROC Curve using Original Model

#Receiver Operating Characteristic(ROC) curve is a plot of the true positive rate against the false positive rate.  
# It shows the tradeoff between sensitivity and specificity.
#tpr (True Positive Rate) = # True positives / # positives = Recall = TP / (TP+FN)
#fpr(False Positive Rate) = # False Positives / # negatives = FP / (FP+TN)

#AUC score for the case is 0.88

y_pred_prob = base_model.predict_proba(X_test)[::,1]
fpr, tpr, _ = metrics.roc_curve(Y_test,  y_pred_prob)
auc = metrics.roc_auc_score(Y_test, y_pred_prob)

plt.figure()
lw = 2
plt.plot(fpr,tpr,color = 'red',label="auc="+str(auc))
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='blue', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic Curve(BASE Model)')

plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()
